      "The text arrives: they're fifteen minutes away. The instinct is to grab the nearest air freshener and fog the hallway. Don't. A last-minute spray blitz is the single most recognizable smell of *someone who just tidied in a panic* — it sits on top of whatever was already there and fades before the second guest takes their coat off.",
      "What actually works is boring and fast: deal with the few things genuinely producing odor, move some air through the house, and set a real scent early enough that it settles into an even, ambient note rather than a fresh spritz. Below is a thirty-minute plan that does exactly that, in order. If you have less time, do steps one and two and skip the polish — the sourcing matters more than anything you can spray.",
      "## Minutes 0–10: The Source Sweep",
      "Most household smell comes from a short list of sources, and in ten focused minutes you can neutralize nearly all of them. Move through these in order and don't get pulled into deep cleaning — you are removing odor, not reorganizing the house.",
      "| Source | Why it smells | The 60-second fix |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Kitchen trash | Damp scraps and packaging ferment fast | Tie it off and take it out now, even if half-full |\n| Sink & dishes | Standing water and food residue go sour | Clear the sink; run the disposal with hot water |\n| Bathroom | The room guests judge most | Wipe the toilet rim and seat, swap in a dry hand towel |\n| Shoes by the door | The first thing anyone smells walking in | Move them to a closet or a closed tray |\n| Pet bowls & litter | Old food and the box carry across rooms | Wash the bowls; scoop the litter and bag it |",
      "Two of these punch far above their weight. The **trash** is almost always the loudest smell in a kitchen, and it leaves the moment the bag does. The **shoes and entry** are what greets every guest before they have taken three steps inside, so clearing them resets the whole first impression. Hit those two even if you do nothing else on the list.",
      "## Minutes 10–15: Air It Out, Fast",
      "While your hands are busy with the sweep, get the air moving — this runs in parallel, it doesn't cost you extra time. Open two windows on different sides of the house to create a cross-breeze, and if you have a window or door at opposite ends, open both so stale air actually flushes out instead of just stirring. Five to ten minutes of real airflow does more to lift a closed-up, lived-in smell than any product, because it removes the odor rather than layering over it.",
      "Run the range hood if you cooked recently, and crack the bathroom window or run its fan after that quick wipe-down. Then close the windows again before your scent step so you're not venting the fragrance you're about to set. Clean, moved air is the foundation everything else sits on.",
      "[[cta]]Shop Home Diffusers|/home",
      "## Minutes 15–20: Focus on What Guests Smell First",
